  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue: The crash occurs after running
gvn-sink because the pass produces invalid IR: a phi node with inline asm values
as incoming operands (\"Cannot take the address of an inline asm!\"). The
reproducer shows a PHI of type ptr with incoming values that are inline asm call
callee operands:  %.sink1 = phi ptr [ asm sideeffect ..., %sw.bb1 ], [ asm
sideeffect ..., %sw.bb ]. Inline asm values (the InlineAsm callee objects) are
not first-class; forming a PHI over them is invalid. GVNSink incorrectly tries to
sink the inline asm call instructions across predecessors and introduces a PHI
for the callee operand.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log: The pass runs and verification
fails on the generated PHI. The log shows no other transformations; the first
mutation leading to failure is in GVNSink creating the PHI. The alias/modref info
is irrelevant here. The verifier detects the illegal PHI containing inline asm
values. This matches a transformation in sinkLastInstruction where PHIs are built
for differing operands. The analysis phase (analyzeInstructionForSinking)
determines which operands need PHIs. It attempts to avoid creating PHIs for call
targets via a heuristic located at lines 698-701: // Don't create indirect calls!
The called value is the final operand. if ((isa<CallInst>(I0) ||
isa<InvokeInst>(I0)) && OpNum == E - 1 && PHI.areAnyIncomingValuesConstant())
return std::nullopt; However, a PHI on the callee (inline asm) was still created,
so this check did not trigger.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis: The code assumes for
CallInst/InvokeInst that the \"called value is the final operand\" (OpNum == E -
1). This is incorrect in LLVM IR: the callee is operand 0; subsequent operands
are the arguments. Thus the heuristic never examines the callee; instead it
examines the last argument. Consequently GVNSink allows forming a PHI for operand
0 (callee) when callees differ between predecessors, leading to constructing a
PHI of inline asm (invalid) or turning a direct call into an indirect one. In the
reproducer, each predecessor ends with a distinct inline asm call (different
InlineAsm objects), so operand 0 differs, GVNSink builds a PHI of those InlineAsm
values, and verifier aborts. The fix must prevent PHI creation on the callee
operand or abort sinking if the callee differs.\n\n4. Proposed Edit
Points(s):\nEdit lines 698-701 in GVNSink.cpp inside
analyzeInstructionForSinking. Replace the incorrect assumption and logic with a
correct treatment of call/invoke operands:\n- Recognize operand 0 as the
callee.\n- If operand 0 differs across predecessors, do not sink this instruction
(return std::nullopt) to avoid introducing a callee PHI (which could produce an
indirect call or invalid IR for inline asm).\n- If operand 0 is the same, skip
attempting to create a PHI for it (continue) so we only consider argument
operands.\nThis removes reliance on incorrect OpNum==E-1 logic and directly
prevents generating PHIs of InlineAsm.\nSuggested replacement code:\n// Do not
create PHIs for the callee of a call or invoke. Operand 0 is the callee.\nif
(isa<CallInst>(I0) || isa<InvokeInst>(I0)) {\n  if (OpNum == 0) {\n    // If
callees differ we cannot sink the instruction.\n    if
(!PHI.areAllIncomingValuesSame())\n      return std::nullopt;\n    // Callee
identical: skip creating a PHI for it.\n    continue;\n  }\n}\nRemove the old
incorrect comment and condition. This ensures inline asm callees are never placed
in PHIs; if they differ sinking is aborted.\n\n5. Conclusion: The bug stems from
a mistaken assumption about operand ordering for calls/invokes causing formation
of an illegal PHI over inline asm callee values. Correcting the operand index
logic prevents generating invalid IR and avoids indirect call creation. After
this fix, gvn-sink will no longer crash or produce the invalid PHI for the
reproducer; the pass will simply refuse to sink those differing inline asm calls,
preserving correctness.",
